Rebooting TiddlyWiki for Node.js and the Browser

Introduction

What is TiddlyWiki?

TiddlyWiki is a JavaScript wiki that can run entirely in the browser, or under Node.js.

It was first released 10 years ago (before jQuery!). TiddlyWiki5 began in 2011, and is currently in beta.

https://github.com/Jermolene/TiddlyWiki5

WhatProblem

What Problem Does TiddlyWiki Solve?

Many people believe that they would be happier and more successful if they were more organised, and that getting there is just a matter of getting the right habits and tools in place.

Computers and the web are fantastic tools for organising stuff. But for most people, the ability to express ourselves and communicate online is beholden to the drifting (often hostile)business model of a foreign corporation.

The alternative of looking after a server is hard. Verifying that your data is secure and private is hard.

UserExperience

TiddlyWiki User Experience

TiddlyWiki has a simple user experience based on a small number of features that work together in combination:

  • Tiddlers (consisting of fields)
  • Links (and backlinks, missing and orphans)
  • Tags
  • Search
  • Transclusion
  • Images are first class citizens with text

Features

More Features

  • Story views for visualising tiddler sequences
  • Multi-language support for the user interface and your content
  • Themes
  • Colour palettes
  • System Tags
  • Static Renderings
  • Plugins: MarkDown, D3, CodeMirror

SingleFileDemo

Demo of Single File Edition

How an end user might use TiddlyWiki

  1. Visit http://tiddlywiki.com/empty.html in Chrome
  2. Copy and paste part of an HTML page
  3. Drag an image from the file system
  4. Drag task management tiddler from http://tiddlywiki.com and add tasks
  5. Save using Chrome
  6. Inspect source
  7. Reload in Firefox, use TiddlyFox
  8. Enable encryption, resave, check source
  9. Apps for smartphones!

RenderingPipeline

TiddlyWiki Rendering Pipeline

Like Angular and Ractive. Not string based; always uses a DOM and selective updating.

Show how sidebar state is held in $:/state/sidebar:

$tw.wiki.addTiddler(new $tw.Tiddler({title: "$:/state/sidebar",text: "yes"}))

BeingCrossPlatform

Running on the Browser and Node.js

Easy.

Smallish boot kernel. Pluggable Common/JS 1.0-compatible modules based on tiddlers.

Test framework based on Jasmine.

Node.js

Running TiddlyWiki Under Node.js

Creating a single file wiki

tiddlywiki mywiki --init tw5.com
tiddlywiki mywiki --rendertiddler $:/core/save/all index.html text/plain

See the template for the HTML, and for some of the CSS.

Serving a wiki over HTTP

tiddlywiki my2wiki --init server
tiddlywiki my2wiki --server

Other options

PouchDB - from Jon Udell's Thali project - https://gist.github.com/judell/9744381

ServerSync

TiddlyWiki Server Synchronisation

The same syncer module is used in the browser and the server.

TiddlyDesktop

Enter node-webkit and TiddlyDesktop

If you are a full stack JavaScript developer that knows node.js and the DOM, then node-webkit will make you feel like somebody from France discovering they can speak French in Canada.

Access the file system from a browser event handler. Use Canvas on the server. Take web page thumbnails. Give your server a synchronous GUI.

TiddlyDesktop is a custom browser with extensions to support working with TiddlyWiki.

Using TiddlyWiki as a Library

Using TiddlyWiki as a Library

/*

A sample node.js application that uses TiddlyWiki5 as a library

*/

var $tw = {};

require("../TiddlyWiki5/boot/bootprefix.js").bootprefix($tw)

// Dummy command line arguments telling TW5 not to load a wiki from the filesystem
$tw.boot = $tw.boot || {};
$tw.boot.argv = ["*"];

require("../TiddlyWiki5/boot/boot.js").TiddlyWiki($tw);

// Boot TiddlyWiki
$tw.boot.boot();

// Add some tiddlers
$tw.wiki.addTiddler({
        title: "TiddlerOne",
        text: "Text of tiddler one, incorporating the {{TiddlerTwo}}",
        tags: ["alpha", "beta"]
});
$tw.wiki.addTiddler({
        title: "TiddlerTwo",
        text: "Text of tiddler two"
});

// Render a tiddler as HTML
var html = $tw.wiki.renderTiddler("text/html","TiddlerOne");
console.log(html);

End
